TY  - JOUR
T1  - Resource Management In Dyadic Competitive Rivalry: The Effects of Resource Bundling and Deployment
AU  - Sirmon, David G.
AU  - Gove, Steve
AU  - Hitt, Michael A.
Y1  - 2008/10/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2008.34789656
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2008.34789656
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 919
EP  - 935
VL  - 51
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Although resources are instrumental to a competitive advantage, management must effectively bundle and deploy an organization's resources for an advantage to be realized. Despite their importance, little research has examined these managerial actions. Using a sample of competitive dyads, we tested theory regarding the effects of rivals' comparative resource stocks and managers' bundling and deployment actions on competitive outcomes. Results indicate that both comparative advantages in resource stocks and managerial actions affect performance. However, their efficacy depends on contextual factors and the deployment flexibility of specific resources. Thus, resource management actions are critical to achieving and sustaining competitive advantage.
AB  - Although resources are instrumental to a competitive advantage, management must effectively bundle and deploy an organization's resources for an advantage to be realized. Despite their importance, little research has examined these managerial actions. Using a sample of competitive dyads, we tested theory regarding the effects of rivals' comparative resource stocks and managers' bundling and deployment actions on competitive outcomes. Results indicate that both comparative advantages in resource stocks and managerial actions affect performance. However, their efficacy depends on contextual factors and the deployment flexibility of specific resources. Thus, resource management actions are critical to achieving and sustaining competitive advantage.
