TY  - JOUR
T1  - Gone but Not Lost: The Different Performance Impacts of Employee Mobility Between Cooperators Versus Competitors
AU  - Somaya, Deepak
AU  - Williamson, Ian O.
AU  - Lorinkova, Natalia
Y1  - 2008/10/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2008.34789660
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2008.34789660
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 936
EP  - 953
VL  - 51
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article extends research on the relationship between employee mobility and firm performance by exploring how mobility between competitors and mobility between potential cooperators are different. We draw on social capital theory to argue that movement of employees both to and from clients may enhance firm performance, whereas only inward mobility from competitors benefits firms. We also hypothesize that it is more harmful for firms to lose social capital-laden human assets to competitors than to other potential employee destinations. We tested our hypotheses with a novel dyadic data set of patent attorney movements between law firms and Fortune 500 companies.
AB  - This article extends research on the relationship between employee mobility and firm performance by exploring how mobility between competitors and mobility between potential cooperators are different. We draw on social capital theory to argue that movement of employees both to and from clients may enhance firm performance, whereas only inward mobility from competitors benefits firms. We also hypothesize that it is more harmful for firms to lose social capital-laden human assets to competitors than to other potential employee destinations. We tested our hypotheses with a novel dyadic data set of patent attorney movements between law firms and Fortune 500 companies.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2008.34789660
